---
export const updateMeta = {
  date: '2026-05-25',
  title: 'Heat tracking workflow page refresh: evaluation checklist + lineage integration + species neutrality',
  tags: ['workflows', 'heat-tracking', 'seo', 'content'],
};
---
<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">May 25, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Refreshed <a href="/workflows/heat-tracking" class="text-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] hover:underline">/workflows/heat-tracking</a> from an AirOps content review. The suggested rewrite was ~80% paraphrase of existing copy, so we cherry-picked the genuinely new material and additionally neutralized the page's dog-specific language so it reads correctly for all nine species.</p>

  <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-700">
    <p><strong>What was added:</strong></p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
      <li>Lineage-connection paragraph after the intro, framing heat tracking as one part of a complete program record alongside pedigrees, COI, and health testing.</li>
      <li>Species coverage line listing all nine supported species (dogs, cats, horses, goats, sheep, cattle, alpacas, llamas, rabbits).</li>
      <li>New <em>"What to look for in any heat and lineage tracking system"</em> section with a 9-row evaluation checklist table (feature / why it matters), positioned between the "What proper heat tracking requires" section and the BreederHQ pitch.</li>
      <li>Marketplace-signal paragraph in the BreederHQ section: program data maintained privately can surface as verifiable signals on the public listing.</li>
      <li>New bullet in the "Built for breeders who" list: heat and cycle data connected to pedigree, COI, and health records in one place.</li>
      <li>Two new FAQ entries (added to both the rendered section and the schema.org FAQPage JSON-LD): heat tracking connecting to pedigree and lineage records, and tracking lineage / COI alongside cycle data.</li>
      <li>Updated the existing species FAQ to enumerate all nine species rather than the vague "cats, rabbits, and other animals" wording. The schema.org array and the rendered FAQ section are now in sync on this entry.</li>
      <li>Synced the rendered "What if I work with a reproductive vet?" FAQ with the richer schema.org version (the second-opinion-not-replacement framing).</li>
      <li>Brought the BreederHQ section's progesterone copy in line with the FAQ array's longer Scout AI Repro Insight description (pattern-level insights across program history).</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Species-neutral language pass (separate from the AirOps suggestion):</strong></p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
      <li>"Stud dog unavailable" → "Sire unavailable"</li>
      <li>"You may not remember which dog it was for" → "which animal it was for"</li>
      <li>"The average dog cycles every 6-8 months. Your dog cycles..." → "Species averages give you a starting point. Your animal cycles..."</li>
      <li>"Confirm stud availability" → "Confirm sire availability"</li>
      <li>"Coordinate with stud owners or reproductive vets" → "Coordinate with sire owners or reproductive vets"</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>What was deliberately skipped:</strong></p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-1">
      <li><em>"Last updated: June 2026"</em> stamp — not used on workflow pages.</li>
      <li>The AirOps species list (only listed 8 species, missing cattle). Our cattle-inclusive 9-species enumeration was used instead per the platform's locked supported-species set.</li>
      <li>Wholesale rewrites of the headline, TL;DR, intro, common-methods sections, and why-they-fail sections — paraphrase, would have been churn.</li>
      <li>The AirOps version weakened the existing progesterone FAQ. Kept the richer existing version.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Also replaced one em dash inside the BreederHQ section with a comma, per the platform-wide ban on em dashes in breeder-facing prose.</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-600">Comparison table widens the layout to <code>max-w-5xl</code> within that one section only; the rest of the page stays at <code>max-w-4xl</code>. Background alternation: gray (Section 4) → white (Section 5) → gray (new Section 5.5) → orange (Section 6).</p>
  </div>
</article>
